## The Core Themes (What We Say)

Every piece of content should land on one or more of these themes. They sit *underneath* the four pillars in [`../documentation/06-content-strategy.md`](../documentation/06-content-strategy.md): pillars are *the kind of content beat* (Scripture Applied / The Grind / Real Talk / The Vision); themes are *the substance the beat is about*.

### 1. He is governed
Self-mastery as the foundation. A man under authority — God's, Scripture's, the Spirit's — is the man who can be trusted with anything else: his appetites, his time, a wife eventually, kids, money, work. A man without self-control is a city without walls; whoever's loudest walks in.

### 2. He kills what's killing him
Scripture's word is *put to death.* Not manage. Not balance. Not "work on it." Kill. Lust, laziness, bitterness, cowardice, the version of him that scrolls instead of prays. The therapy-frame — "be gentle with yourself," "do the work," "your journey" — sounds healthy and produces nothing. Scripture is more violent and more honest. ETHOS speaks bluntly here, especially about porn and the phone.

### 3. He works
Work isn't the curse — futility is. The 20s aren't a holding pattern; they're the forge. A man's not measured by income but by *usefulness* — the kind of man someone would hire, marry, depend on. Show up early. Do hard things on purpose. Learn a skill that pays. Stop waiting to feel like it.

### 4. He tells the truth
Integrity means one man across contexts — no church version, gym version, girl-he-likes version, late-night-private-browser version. Hidden men rot. Confessed men heal. In a world of curation and performance, plain speech is a rare weapon.

### 5. He's strong AND tender — in the right places
Most men reverse this: hard with their girlfriend, mom, the waiter; soft with their sin. The righteous man flips it — ruthless with his own flesh, gentle with the people God gave him. Jesus wept *and* flipped tables. Either alone is a caricature.

### 6. He leads by giving himself away
Christ's leadership got him killed for the people he was leading. That's the model — not "I'm the man so obey me." It's "I go first into the cost." Leadership in Scripture is sacrificial, not domineering. First to apologize, first to serve, first to take the hit. Tate's dominance is a different universe.

### 7. He's planted in real men
Not online. Not parasocial. Not a podcast or a Discord. Real men in the room — at least two or three with his phone number, who know his sin, can tell him he's full of it, will show up. Iron sharpens iron only with contact and friction.

### 8. He chases God, not a wife
Order matters. The man desperate for a wife radiates desperation; the kind of woman he actually wants can smell it from across the room. The man walking with God *becomes* the man worth marrying. Get the order wrong and the rest goes wrong.

### 9. He fights the phone
This is the 2026-specific battle his grandfather didn't have. The phone is the new tavern, the new mistress, the new idol — where lust lives, where envy lives, where time dies. A man who can't put it down has a master, and it isn't Christ. He needs a digital war, not a digital detox.

### 10. He walks humbly
*Do justice. Love kindness. Walk humbly.* Micah's three. He can look another man in the eye AND get on his knees. He's not the main character. He's not self-made. He's dust with breath in his lungs because God is patient. Sturdy, not soft.

These ten aren't a checklist for one post — they're the field of substance. A given piece will sit on one or two and let the rest hum underneath.

